I'll explain how to connect to an SDN (Software-Defined Network) cloud VM from the outside world, covering the complete networking path and setup.

Understanding the Connection Path
When you connect to a cloud VM from anywhere in the world, your traffic goes through several layers:

Your Device → ISP → Internet Backbone → Cloud Provider's Edge → SDN Controller → Virtual Switch → VM

Key Components in SDN Cloud Architecture
SDN Controller: The "brain" that programs routing rules and manages traffic flows centrally

Virtual Switches (vSwitches): Software switches (like Open vSwitch) on hypervisors that forward packets based on SDN controller instructions

Overlay Networks: Virtual networks (using VXLAN, GRE, or Geneve) that tunnel traffic over physical infrastructure

Physical Underlay: The actual network hardware connecting data centers

Routing in SDN Cloud Environments
Traditional routing uses distributed protocols (BGP, OSPF), but SDN centralizes this:

External routing: BGP announces your VM's public IP to the internet
Edge routing: Traffic enters the cloud provider's network through edge routers
SDN fabric: The controller programs flow rules to direct traffic through the virtual network
VM delivery: vSwitch on the host applies final forwarding rules to reach your VM
